PERTINENT ONCOLOGIC HISTORY
1.  2009--onset of hematochezia.  It worsened in November 2009.  She also had a 20- to 25-pound weight-loss which she attributes primarily to her decreased mobility from sciatica.
2.  January 29, 2010, colonoscopy revealed ulcerated mass in the midrectum.  Also noted was a 5-cm villous neoplasm just inside the dentate.  Pathology from the midrectum showed moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma, and biopsies from the distal rectum also showed tubulovillous adenocarcinoma with areas of mucinous adenocarcinoma.  Staging scan showed no evidence of distant spread.  Her CEA was elevated to 36.5.
3.  February 2010--she began neoadjuvant radiation therapy with Xeloda.  She did not tolerate the treatment well.  She became dehydrated, developed bloody diarrhea, hypoalbuminemia, and a DVT.  She was hospitalized, and treatment was stopped.
4.  March 2010 while at-home had a left popliteal thrombus and was put on anticoagulation.
5.  May 7, 2010, APR with resection of the primary rectal carcinoma. Four of twenty-one nodes were positive for metastatic disease.
She is making good headway recovering from her surgery.  She has an appointment with Thrombophilia Clinic later today.  She has noted no lumps or bumps other than a hematoma that formed on her arm while blood pressure was being checked today.  Overall, she is feeling well.

